{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601912"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:20:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:20:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15673"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15673"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.8,0,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8364"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62203"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8364"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15673"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47649"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4090"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8412"},{"type":"tags","id":"8504"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20163"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20166"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62203"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with heavy menstrual bleeding for the past six months. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A pelvic ultrasound reveals a 3 cm intramural fibroid arising from the middle layer of the uterine wall.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following layers of the uterine wall is the most likely site of origin of this fibroid?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endometrium","Myometrium","Perimetrium","Parametrium","Mesometrium"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with menorrhagia and is found to have an intramural fibroid. Fibroids (leiomyomas) most commonly arise from the \u003Cstrong\u003Emyometrium\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the middle and thickest layer of the uterine wall, composed of smooth muscle fibres arranged in circular and longitudinal bundles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrium\u003C/strong\u003E is the innermost layer of the uterus, consisting of glandular epithelium that undergoes cyclical changes during the menstrual cycle. While submucosal fibroids can protrude into the endometrial cavity, they originate from the myometrium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eperimetrium\u003C/strong\u003E is the outer serous layer of the uterus, continuous with the peritoneum. It is a thin layer that provides a smooth external surface and is not typically associated with fibroid formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eparametrium\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the connective tissue between the layers of the broad ligament that extends laterally from the uterus and upper vagina. It is not a layer of the uterine wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emesometrium\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the broad ligament that supports the uterus, not a layer of the uterine wall itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding uterine anatomy is crucial for interpreting imaging findings and planning surgical management of fibroids. The myometrial origin of fibroids explains their typical appearance on ultrasound and their response to hormonal influences.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The myometrium is the middle and thickest layer of the uterine wall, composed of smooth muscle.","The myometrium is responsible for uterine contractions during labour and menstruation.","The three layers of the uterine wall from inside to out are endometrium, myometrium, and perimetrium."],"references":["Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Kovacs, W. J., \u0026 Ojeda, S. R. (Eds.). (2012). Textbook of endocrine physiology. OUP USA","Ciarmela P, Islam MS, Reis FM, Gray PC, Bloise E, Petraglia F, Vale W, Castellucci M. Growth factors and myometrium: biological effects in uterine fibroid and possible clinical implications. Hum Reprod Update. 2011 Nov-Dec;17(6):772-90. doi: 10.1093/humupd/dmr031. Epub 2011 Jul 25. PMID: 21788281; PMCID: PMC3191937.","Lethaby A, Vollenhoven B. Fibroids (uterine myomatosis, leiomyomas). BMJ Clin Evid. 2011 Jan 11;2011:0814. PMID: 21477393; PMCID: PMC3217738."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47649"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15673"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47649"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T12:52:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T12:52:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8364"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62203"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tag